  "grammarNote": {
    "title": "Existence: いる and ある",
    "explanation": "Japanese uses two verbs for 'to exist': いる for living things (people, animals) and ある for non-living things (objects, places). The thing that exists is marked with the particle が: 海がある (There is a sea), 人がいる (There is a person). が marks the subject — the thing being presented as new information. ない is the negative of ある: 家がない (There is no house).",
    "examples": [
